"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077666","Treasury","false","2019-03-04","<p>The information requested could be provided only at disproportionate cost. Data on unpaid penalties owed to HMRC are not readily available. HMRC does not produce figures on unpaid penalties for all heads of duty where a penalty charge would apply.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077666/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:18:33.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077666/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077666/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-26","Revenue and Customs: Unpaid Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much HMRC has been owed in unpaid penalties in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","226144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077667","Treasury","false","2019-03-04","<p>As of 3rd April 2017, HMRC has brought together the High Net Worth Unit and Affluent teams to form a single Wealthy team. The figures below are the personal tax paid by high net worth individuals (income tax, national insurance and capital gains tax).</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Estimated tax receipts</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009 - 10</p></td><td><p>£5.10bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010 - 11</p></td><td><p>£3.7bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011 - 12</p></td><td><p>£3.79bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012 - 13</p></td><td><p>£3.13bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 - 14</p></td><td><p>£4.79bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 - 15</p></td><td><p>£4.34bn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£4.3bn</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077667/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:32:37.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077667/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077667/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-26","Tax Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the contribution to the public purse from the work of the HMRC specialist unit for collecting tax from high net worth individuals in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014, (f) 2015, (g) 2016, (h) 2017, and (i) 2018.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","226145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077668","Treasury","false","2019-03-04","<p>As of 3rd April 2017, HMRC has brought together the High Net Worth Unit and Affluent teams to form a single Wealthy team.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office’s report on “collecting tax from high net worth individuals” advised that as of 2015-16 there were 6,500 high net worth individuals. It reported around a third of the High Net Worth Unit’s customers were subject to an enquiry at the time of the report.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077668/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:25:19.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077668/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077668/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-26","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many high net worth individuals HMRC investigated in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014, (f) 2015, (g) 2016, (h) 2017 and (i) 2018.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","226146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077669","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-04","<p>There are clear rules in place requiring that undersized catches of species not yet subject to the landing obligation, such as bass, are not retained on board, trans-shipped, landed, transported, stored, sold, displayed or offered for sale, but shall be returned immediately to the sea. This is a long standing principle which will continue to be enforced accordingly.</p><p> </p><p>Inshore Fisheries and Conservation Authorities (IFCAs) are independent statutory authorities and have direct responsibility for the protection of sea fisheries resources in their districts, and for the sustainable management of their exploitation. When an activity is occurring, or may occur, that is likely to impact the marine environment, the IFCA, as regulator, is expected to consider the significance of this within its district. Cornwall IFCA recently considered using its powers under Section 157(2) of the Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009 to introduce an emergency byelaw to address bass netting issues. However, this was judged to not fully meet the qualifying criteria for an emergency byelaw as stated in the Act and could potentially be challenged on those grounds.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077669/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T12:17:39.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077669/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077669/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-02-26","Sea Bass","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department will take to tackle the problem of illegal landing of undersized bass; and for what reason the Cornwall Inshore Fisheries and Conservation Authority might face a legal challenge if they prohibited gill net meshes from 89 mm to 109 mm in order to stop this practice.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","226177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077671","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-06","<p>We will ensure the Bishop of Truro is well supported and has the resources needed throughout the duration of the review he chairs. Final figures for the cost of the review will be published in due course.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077671/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T15:03:10.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077671/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077671/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-02-26","Christianity: Oppression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what budget has been allocated to the independent review of his Department's work on supporting persecuted Christians.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","226108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077672","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-06","<p>The Rebalancing Medicines Legislation and Pharmacy Regulation Programme Board met on 18 October 2018 and 23 November 2018 to discuss the responses received to the public consultation on the draft Pharmacy (Preparation and Dispensing Errors – Hospital and Other Pharmacy Services) Order 2018 and the draft Pharmacy (Responsible Pharmacists, Superintendent Pharmacists etc.) Order 2018.</p><p> </p><p>After considering the responses received at length, the Board has recommended that all proposals made in respect of the two draft Orders are progressed - albeit with minor amendments to the draft Pharmacy (Responsible Pharmacists, Superintendent Pharmacists etc.) Order 2018. These proposed amendments will be subject to agreement with Parliamentary Counsel.</p><p> </p><p>The Department remains committed to laying the two draft Orders before Parliament as quickly as possible, subject to legal and Parliamentary time and European Union exit preparations. The Government’s response to the consultation will be laid in Parliament alongside the draft legislation.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077672/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T11:05:32.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077672/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077672/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-26","Pharmacy: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when his Department plans to publish the outcome of the consultation on Pharmacy legislation on dispensing errors and organisational governance.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","226026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077673","Home Office","false","2019-03-04","<p>The date from which leave for the month of April 2019 for staff of the National Crime Agency was no longer authorised was 14 January 2019</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077673/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T16:48:59.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077673/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077673/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-26","National Crime Agency: Holiday Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 19 February 2019 to Question 221553 on National Crime Agency: Brexit, since what date has leave for the month of April 2019 for staff of the National Crime Agency no longer been authorised.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","226012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077674","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-06","<p>The statistic referenced is cited in a report &quot;<em>Response to Persecution: Findings of the Under Caesar's Sword Project on Global Christian Communities&quot;, </em>led by the Notre Dame Centre for Ethics and Culture, the Religious Freedom Institute, and Georgetown University's Religious Freedom Research Project. In addition, a 2016 Pew Research Centre study found that Christians were the most widely targeted group in 144 countries, up from 128 in 2015.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077674/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T15:04:24.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077674/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077674/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-02-26","Christianity: Oppression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which studies informed his statement at the launch of the independent review of his Department's work in supporting persecuted Christians that 80 per cent of people who experience religious persecution are Christian.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","226109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077676","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-04","<p>Having regard to the need to protect personal information the Department does not consider it would be appropriate to itemise the amount paid to individual barristers. It would also involve the Department in disproportionate cost to identify the fees paid specifically to some barristers rather than their chambers or for HS2 matters alone.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077676/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T14:58:34.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077676/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077676/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-26","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been disbursed from the public purse on barristers' legal fees and expenses for work relating to High Speed Two to (a) James Eadie QC, (b) Tim Mould QC, (c) James Strachan QC, (d) Justine Thornton QC, (e) Philip Moser QC, (f) Karen Steyn QC, (g) Jemima Stratford QC, (h) James Maurici QC, (i) Lisa Busch (now QC), (j) Andrew Sharland (now QC), (k) Julian Milford, (l) Richard Wald, (m) John Joliffe, (n) Jacqueline Lean, (o) Richard Turney, (p) Mark Westmoreland-Smith and (q) Clare Parry since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","226005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077677","Department for Education","false","2019-03-06","<p>On 28 January 2019, the Department for Education published allocations from the additional £400 million announced at Budget 2018. Payments were made at the beginning of February through the same routes as devolved formula capital (DFC). As with DFC, individual allocations vary according to the number and phase of education of pupils in a school. An average primary and secondary school have been allocated at least £10,000 and £50,000 respectively. Individual allocations and an explanation of the methodology used to calculate them, are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-allocations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-allocations</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077677/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T13:41:25.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077677/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077677/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-02-26","Schools: Birmingham Selly Oak","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the commitment in Budget 2018, when schools in Birmingham, Selly Oak constituency will receive the one-off capital payment of (a) £10,000 to each primary school and (b) £50,000 to each secondary school.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","226027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077678","Cabinet Office","false","2019-03-04","<p>Members of the Ministerial Group have met informally to discuss the work of the group and to hear from experts and the Chair also meets with members of the group individually. The Group has met twice formally since its inception in July 2018, once in November 2018 and once in February 2019.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministerial Group Chair is supported by a private secretary who has portfolio responsibility from within the Office of the Leader of the House of Commons. The secretariat function for the Early Years Family Support Ministerial Group is provided by the Economic and Domestic Affairs Secretariat in the Cabinet Office. The group draws on resources from HM Treasury, Department for Work and Pensions, Department for Education, Department for Health and Social Care, the Ministry of Housing, Communications, and Local Government, and Home Office.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077678/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T10:36:58.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077678/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077678/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-02-26","Early Years Ministerial Group On Family Support","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on how many occasions the ministerial group on family support has met since its inception on 27 July 2018.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","226113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077679","Department for Education","false","2019-03-06","<p>Schools can spend their allocations from the additional £400 million announced at Budget 2018 on capital projects to meet their own priorities. This may include improvements to buildings, equipment, and other facilities, such as ICT. The individual allocations for schools and other eligible institutions are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-allocations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-allocations</a>. Payments were made at the beginning of February through the same routes as devolved formula capital.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077679/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T13:45:09.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077679/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077679/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-02-26","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what schools are able to spend their one-off capital payment announced in Budget 2018 on.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","226028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077681","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-03-04","<p>We do not comment on the operational deployments of RC-135W Rivet Joint as to do so would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077681/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T16:36:08.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077681/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077681/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-02-26","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether UK RC-135W Rivet Joint aircraft are operating over Yemen in support of the Saudi-led coalition.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","226193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077682","Department for International Development","false","2019-03-04","<p>Through UK Aid Connect, DFID will provide funding to a consortium led by the Institute of Development Studies to collect data on marginalised religious or belief groups in a way which does not put those groups at risk. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is supporting a project to explore models for better data on Freedom of Religion or Belief through the Magna Carta Fund.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077682/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T14:57:48.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077682/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077682/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-02-26","Developing Countries: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to collect data on marginalised religious or belief groups in countries in which her Department operates in a way which does not put those groups at risk.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","226110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077683","Department for Education","false","2019-03-04","<p>We will be spending around £6 billion on childcare support in 2019-20 - a record amount. That will include funding for our early education entitlements, on which we plan to spend around £3.5 billion this year alone.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities receive funding from central government for delivering the free early years entitlements to 3 and 4 year olds through the dedicated schools grant. Our provisional allocations to local authorities for 2018-19 can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2018-to-2019</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are responsible for setting the funding rates for their early years providers in consultation with their schools forum. Data from local authority planned expenditure for 2018-19 is publicly available. The data, as reported by local authorities, is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/planned-la-and-school-expenditure-2018-to-2019-financial-year" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/planned-la-and-school-expenditure-2018-to-2019-financial-year</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The government recognises the need to keep the evidence base on costs and charges up to date. The mean hourly fee charged by providers in England in Spring 2018 was estimated to be £5.02 for children under age 2, £5.01 for children aged 2 and £4.92 for 3 and 4 year old preschool children. Details can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2018</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to monitor the provider market closely through a range of regular and one-off research projects which provide insight into various aspects of the provider market.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077683/answer",,,,,"226095","2019-03-04T13:31:18.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077683/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077683/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-02-26","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the article entitled UK free childcare funding woes forcing some providers out of business, published by the Financial Times on 28 April 2018, what assessment his Department has made of the accuracy of reports that the 30 hours’ free childcare for working parents of three and four year olds is underfunded; and what assessment he has made of the effect of the level of Government funding provided for that childcare on the fees charged by providers to parents of younger children.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","226097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077685","Cabinet Office","false","2019-03-04","<p>Members of the Ministerial Group have met informally to discuss the work of the group and to hear from experts and the Chair also meets with members of the group individually. The Group has met twice formally since its inception in July 2018, once in November 2018 and once in February 2019.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministerial Group Chair is supported by a private secretary who has portfolio responsibility from within the Office of the Leader of the House of Commons. The secretariat function for the Early Years Family Support Ministerial Group is provided by the Economic and Domestic Affairs Secretariat in the Cabinet Office. The group draws on resources from HM Treasury, Department for Work and Pensions, Department for Education, Department for Health and Social Care, the Ministry of Housing, Communications, and Local Government, and Home Office.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077685/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T10:37:19.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077685/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077685/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-02-26","Early Years Ministerial Group On Family Support","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many officials are assigned to work on the Ministerial Group on family support for conception to age two from the (a) Office of the Leader of the House of Commons, (b) HM Treasury, (c) Department for Work and Pensions, (d) Department for Education, (e) Department of Health and Social Care and (f) Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","226114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077686","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-04","<p>The information is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077686/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:33:28.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077686/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077686/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-02-26","Universal Credit: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 February 2019 to Question 216934, on Universal Credit: Disqualification, how many universal credit claimants have been sanctioned for refusing to accept the offer of a job with a zero hours contract.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","226013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077687","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-04","<p>For the last completed financial year, 2017/18, the total number of claimants helped through Universal Support Assisted Digital Support by Local Authorities was 55,941. This figure is derived from the quarterly returns submitted by Local Authorities as part of the funding arrangement. These figures provided by Local Authorities do not include the large numbers of people helped daily with digital support by Jobcentres, and other organisations, which are unrecorded.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077687/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:37:17.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077687/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077687/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-02-26","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people her Department has helped through its Universal Support Assisted Digital Service.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","226014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077688","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-04","<p>We have not made any such assessment. Compensation orders are made at the discretion of the sentencing court, which must have regard to the offender’s means. Section 130 of the Powers of Criminal Courts (Sentencing) Act 2000 gives the courts power to order a person convicted of a criminal offence, including sexual offending against children, to compensate a victim financially, primarily for personal injury, loss or damage.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that it is important for offenders to make reparation for their crimes, and in recent years this regime has been strengthened by obliging courts to consider making a compensation order in appropriate cases, and lifting the £5,000 cap on compensation awards in respect of offenders aged 18 or over in the magistrates’ court.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077688/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:54:51.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077688/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077688/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-02-26","Sexual Offences: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of the use of compulsory compensation orders in ensuring that adult survivors of childhood sexual abuse receive redress.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","226180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077690","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-04","<p>Everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage should receive it and we will act where employers have been found to be in breach of the law. This Government continues to invest heavily in minimum wage enforcement, almost doubling the budget to £26.3 million for 2018/19, up from £13.2 million in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, the Director of Labour Market Enforcement recommended making changes to the scheme “to increase its compliance and deterrent effect.” Work has now begun on this to ensure the scheme continues to best fulfil this purpose.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077690/answer",,,,,"226133","2019-03-04T13:51:02.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077690/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077690/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-02-26","Minimum Wage: Non-payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reasons his Department has not published the names of the companies who have underpaid the national minimum wage since July 2018.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","226132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077691","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-04","<p>Everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage should receive it and we will act where employers have been found to be in breach of the law. This Government continues to invest heavily in minimum wage enforcement, almost doubling the budget to £26.3 million for 2018/19, up from £13.2 million in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, the Director of Labour Market Enforcement recommended making changes to the scheme “to increase its compliance and deterrent effect.” Work has now begun on this to ensure the scheme continues to best fulfil this purpose.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077691/answer",,,,,"226132","2019-03-04T13:51:02.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077691/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077691/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-02-26","Minimum Wage: Non-payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to publish the names of employers who have underpaid the national minimum wage since July 2018.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","226133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077692","Home Office","false","2019-03-04","<p>We recognise the need for the police to have appropriate resources in place to manage complex child sexual abuse investigations. We have prioritised child sexual abuse as a national threat to empower police forces to maximise their specialist skills and expertise, and have invested significantly in transforming the police response to child sexual abuse through the Police Transformation Fund.</p><p><br>Operation Hydrant was established to co-ordinate efforts across policing to respond to the increasing volume of non-recent child sexual abuse cases being reported. We have supported Operation Hydrant with £11.8m of po-lice Special Grant funding to date. Additionally, the College of Policing has developed bespoke guidance to senior investigating officers managing non-recent investigations.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077692/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:05:04.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077692/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077692/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-26","Sexual Offences: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans his Department has to improve evidence gathering and ensure that the Crown Prosecution Service receives actionable evidence in cases of historic childhood sexual abuse.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","226181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077694","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-04","<p>The Department is providing £51 million (which includes £12 million to set up delivery in the run-up to April 2019) of funding to Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland to deliver the Help to Claim service from April 2019. This was announced by the Government, Citizen’s Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland and Government on 1 October 2018.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077694/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:30:05.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077694/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077694/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-02-26","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what funding has been allocated to the Help to Claim Scheme.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","226015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077695","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) are responsible for enforcing the National Minimum Wage Regulations on behalf of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS).</p><p> </p><p>We have almost doubled the enforcement budget for the National Minimum Wage and National Living Wage to a record high of £26.3 million for 2018/19, up from £13.2 million in 2015/16. There are over 420 HMRC staff involved in the enforcement of the National Minimum Wage Act 1998.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS has robust plans in place to manage delivery of EU exit. No BEIS officials have been redeployed from work on National Minimum Wage enforcement to work on preparations for the UK leaving the EU.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077695/answer",,,,,"226135","2019-03-11T17:40:21.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077695/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077695/answer","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077695/answer/previousversion/105650","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077695/answer/previousversion/105650",,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-02-26","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether any civil servants of his Department have been redeployed from work on national minimum wage enforcement to work on preparations for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","226134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077696","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) are responsible for enforcing the National Minimum Wage Regulations on behalf of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS).</p><p> </p><p>We have almost doubled the enforcement budget for the National Minimum Wage and National Living Wage to a record high of £26.3 million for 2018/19, up from £13.2 million in 2015/16. There are over 420 HMRC staff involved in the enforcement of the National Minimum Wage Act 1998.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS has robust plans in place to manage delivery of EU exit. No BEIS officials have been redeployed from work on National Minimum Wage enforcement to work on preparations for the UK leaving the EU.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077696/answer",,,,,"226134","2019-03-11T17:40:21.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077696/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077696/answer","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077696/answer/previousversion/105651","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077696/answer/previousversion/105651",,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-02-26","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many staff in his Department are working on minimum wage enforcement.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","226135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077697","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-04","<p>Following the publication of the NHS Long Term Plan, the National Implementation Framework, to be published in the spring, will provide further information on how the Long Term Plan will be implemented. Additional details, based on local health system five year plans, will be brought together in a detailed national implementation plan in the autumn.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to work closely with key partners and stakeholders, including the Alzheimer’s Society and other voluntary sector partners, as we support the National Health Service in England to deliver the commitments set out in the Long Term Plan.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077697/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T16:42:13.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077697/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077697/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-26","Dementia: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the NHS Long Term Plan, what proportion of the £4.5 billion allocated to community care will be disbursed to support dementia patients.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","226182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077698","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-04","<p>The Government’s Dementia 2020 Challenge and associated implementation plan describes a programme of action to deliver sustained improvements in dementia care. The Challenge commits to all staff having the training they need by 2020. The requisite training needs are set out in the Dementia Training Standards Framework. Good progress has been made to date in training the social care workforce with around half of those estimated to need tier 2 have undertaken training to a level equivalent to it. The Department is currently exploring options for further increasing take up of tier 2 training to everyone who needs it.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077698/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T16:49:35.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077698/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077698/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-26","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans his Department has to increase the number of social care workers trained to level Tier 2 of the Dementia Training Standards Framework.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","226183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077699","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-05","<p>The Government is determined to get the best deal for the UK in our negotiations to leave the EU, and continues to work with industry to help manage the economic impacts on the livestock sector and other stakeholders in planning for a possible no deal scenario. Whilst it is very likely that third country rules will be applied to EU imports of products of animal origin, contingency options are being developed, and we will not be introducing any new border checks in the immediate aftermath of a no deal scenario. As a result, animal products can come into the UK at any port of entry as they do now to minimise disruption to trade. Only animal products from EU countries with disease outbreak safeguard measures will need to be notified to the UK before arrival.</p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077699/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-05T10:14:19.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077699/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077699/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-02-26","Animal Products: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the effect of leaving the EU without a deal on the cost of transporting animal products from the EU to the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","226016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077700","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-04","<p>The information is not held in the format requested and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077700/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:25:56.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077700/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077700/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-26","Mental Health Services: Merseyside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many (a) available and (b) occupied beds for mental illness were open overnight under the care of consultants in (a) Wirral and (b) Merseyside on average in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","226060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077702","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-05","<p>It is already illegal for a taxi or private hire driver to refuse carriage to a passenger on the grounds that they are accompanied by an assistance dog. Responsibility for ensuring that drivers understand their legal duties, and for taking action against those alleged to have acted discriminatorily, rests with local licensing authorities.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077702/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-05T13:16:13.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077702/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077702/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-26","Taxis: Guide Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Government will publish a timeframe for the introduction of legislation to address discrimination against guide dog owners using taxis.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","226194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077703","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-04","<p>The Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs attended the Clean Air Summit on 14 February with the Liverpool City Region Mayor and city leaders from across the country.</p><p> </p><p>A range of issues were discussed at the Summit including the ambitious goals set out in our new Clean Air Strategy, the need to focus on reducing emissions from a variety of sources, and support for local authorities with powers and funding.</p><p> </p><p>Defra officials have regular and ongoing engagement with those local authorities named in the 2017 Plan for Tackling Roadside Nitrogen Dioxide Concentrations to support them in considering measures to address nitrogen dioxide exceedances in their areas, including Liverpool City Council.</p><p> </p><p>Liverpool City Council have been directed to develop a local plan by 31 October 2019 and on 28 February this year presented an update on their plan to senior representatives in the Joint Air Quality Unit.</p><p> </p><p>Due to the highly localised nature of the problem, local knowledge is crucial in solving pollution problems in these hotspots. Local authorities, including Liverpool, are considering a range of measures to tackle their nitrogen dioxide exceedances, including, where appropriate, charging Clean Air Zones.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077703/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T09:19:17.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077703/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077703/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-02-26","Air Pollution: Liverpool City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Liverpool City Region Mayor on tackling air pollution in the Liverpool City Region area.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","226061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077704","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-04","<p>Auditors of health assessment reports on claimants of Personal Independence Payment are not independent of DWP; they are independent of the Assessment Providers.</p><p> </p><p>The DWP independent audit function, which was rolled out across the contracts in 2016, is used to judge how the providers are performing against set quality targets to ensure that the advice provided to the Department’s decision makers is of suitable quality, fully explained and justified.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077704/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T16:51:45.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077704/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077704/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-02-26","Personal Independence Payment: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, to what extent auditors of health assessment reports on claimants of personal independence payment are independent from her Department.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","226157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077705","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-04","<p>At this stage the study is aimed at developing a better understanding of the behaviour of a range of cladding products when exposed to fire and their possible contribution to fire spread.</p><p>The performance criteria and how they will be measured are highlighted in table 2 of the methodology. A copy of the methodology is available in the House library.</p><p>The findings of the research will help determine, in consultation with the Independent Expert Panel, any further action we should take. This could include further testing at large scale and/or advice to building owners.</p><p>My department published an advice note on external wall systems that do not incorporate Aluminium Composite Material in December 2017 and updated it in December 2018. This advice makes clear to building owners that wall systems on existing buildings may only use materials that are of limited combustibility unless the system has achieved the appropriate BR135 classification via a BS 8414 test. It reiterates that the clearest way to ensure safety is to remove any unsafe materials.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077705/answer",,,,,"226201","2019-03-04T17:28:22.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077705/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077705/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-26","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2019 to Question 217589 on Buildings: Insulation and with reference to the Buildings Research Establishment interim report entitled Fire performance of cladding materials research – experimental methodology and performance criteria, what part of the methodology will enable the Government to determine whether samples are combustible.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","226200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077706","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-04","<p>At this stage the study is aimed at developing a better understanding of the behaviour of a range of cladding products when exposed to fire and their possible contribution to fire spread.</p><p>The performance criteria and how they will be measured are highlighted in table 2 of the methodology. A copy of the methodology is available in the House library.</p><p>The findings of the research will help determine, in consultation with the Independent Expert Panel, any further action we should take. This could include further testing at large scale and/or advice to building owners.</p><p>My department published an advice note on external wall systems that do not incorporate Aluminium Composite Material in December 2017 and updated it in December 2018. This advice makes clear to building owners that wall systems on existing buildings may only use materials that are of limited combustibility unless the system has achieved the appropriate BR135 classification via a BS 8414 test. It reiterates that the clearest way to ensure safety is to remove any unsafe materials.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077706/answer",,,,,"226200","2019-03-04T17:28:22.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077706/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077706/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-26","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Minister for Housing's oral evidence to the Housing, Communities and Local Government Committee on 28 January 2019 on the independent review of building regulations and to the Buildings Research Establishment's interim report entitled Fire performance of cladding materials research – experimental methodology and performance criteria, what measurements within the testing methodology his Department will use to assess whether particular types of cladding should be removed from buildings.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","226201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077707","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-04","<p>Officials have been in regular contact (meetings, emails and phone conversations) with the Building Research Establishment between June 2018 and February 2019. The Department does not keep a record of all the exchanges between officials and the Building Research Establishment.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077707/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T16:06:45.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077707/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077707/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-26","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Buildings Research Establishment interim report entitled Fire performance of cladding materials research – experimental methodology and performance criteria, how many meetings were held between his officials and representatives of the Buildings Research Establishment between 19 June 2018 and 26 February 2019; and if he will publish the dates of those meetings.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","226202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077709","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-03-04","<p>The Type 31e Frigates will be tailored toward maritime security and defence engagement, including the Fleet Ready Escort role at home, our commitments in the South Atlantic, the Caribbean and the Gulf, and to NATO. These ships will fulfil routine tasks to free up the more complex Type 45 Destroyers and Type 26 Frigates for their specialist combat roles in support of the strategic nuclear deterrent and as part of the carrier strike group.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077709/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T16:34:37.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077709/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077709/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-02-26","Type 31 Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Type 31e frigates which are due to be built will form part of the carrier strike.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","226207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077710","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-06","<p>The Government is clear that unfair practices have no place in a modern housing market. That is why we are putting pressure on developers and freeholders to vary onerous lease terms, such as those with doubling ground rents. Some developers have introduced schemes to assist individuals which is welcome, but this support must be extended to include second hand buyers, and leaseholders proactively contacted. We are keeping a close eye on progress and will consider taking further action as necessary.</p><p>We are also working with the Law Commission to make it faster, fairer and cheaper for existing leaseholders to extend their lease or buy the freehold. In addition, we have worked with Trading Standards to ensure there is better information on redress, and they recently published guidance to help leaseholders understand where to go if things go wrong, and how they can access support.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077710/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T11:50:45.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077710/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077710/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-26","Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to help leaseholders with onerous leases.","true","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","226011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077711","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-04","<p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://ckan.publishing.service.gov.uk/dataset/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://ckan.publishing.service.gov.uk/dataset/contracts-finder-archive</a>.</p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a>.</p><p>The Fire Performance of Cladding Materials Research contract can be found at the following address:</p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/88ccc1d7-608b-4631-957b-0e9490abf05d?p=@UFQxUlRRPT0=NjJNT08" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/88ccc1d7-608b-4631-957b-0e9490abf05d?p=@UFQxUlRRPT0=NjJNT08</a>.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077711/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T15:52:55.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077711/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077711/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-26","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the value of the contract awarded by his Department to the Buildings Research Establishment was for research and testing of fire safety standards of non-ACM cladding.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","226203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077712","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-03-04","<p>The Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 stated our intent to buy 138 F-35 Lightning aircraft over the life of the programme. The first tranche of 48 aircraft will be the carrier capable F-35B, of which 17 have been delivered so far. Decisions on subsequent tranches of Lightning will be taken at the appropriate time.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077712/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T16:33:39.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077712/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077712/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-02-26","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government plans to allocate funding for the purchase of F-35A or F-35B aircraft; and what assessment he has made of the implications of that decision for the ability of the Royal Air Force to land aircraft on aircraft carriers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","226208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077713","Cabinet Office","false","2019-03-04","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077713/answer","PQ 226065.pdf","PQ 226065.pdf","UKSA Response","UKSA Response",,"2019-03-04T10:16:49.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077713/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077713/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-02-26","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the proportion changes in income for each income quintile from the financial year 2017 to financial year 2018.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","226065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077715","Department for Education","false","2019-03-04","<p>Through the Teaching and Leadership Innovation Fund, the Department for Education is funding Accelerate – a professional development programme that will provide specialist support for early career teachers.</p><p>Accelerate, delivered by the Education Development Trust, is free to eligible teachers in their first five years of teaching. As a part of the programme, schools will be remunerated for teachers or leaders who are involved in aspects of delivery, for example, for coaching participants. No additional funding is provided to cover supply staff costs for staff undertaking the programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077715/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-04T17:57:44.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077715/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077715/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-02-26","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether additional funding will be provided for supply teachers while permanent staff undertake the accelerated teaching programme.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","226211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077716","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-06","<p>The Government does not require landlords to record centrally that they have served a Section 21 notice to their tenants and we have no plans to make them do so.</p><p>However, we collect data through the English Housing Survey on tenants’ reasons for moving out of a private sector property. According to the 2016-17 Private Rented Sector report the majority of tenancies are ended by the tenant themselves or by mutual consent, <br> rather than by the landlord serving an eviction notice.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077716/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T11:51:27.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077716/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077716/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-26","Private Rented Housing: Evictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to record the number of Section 21 notices served to tenants.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","226129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077717","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-06","<p>The following table shows the number of nicotine dependence prescription items dispensed in the community, via an FP10 form, in England 2010-17. There are various other routes in which such medication can be supplied to a patient from the National Health Service including from community pharmacies via voucher schemes and a direct supply to patients from a Patient Group Direction, this data is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Bupropion Hydrochloride</p></td><td><p>Nicotine replacement therapy</p></td><td><p>Varenicline Tartrate</p></td><td><p>Total nicotine dependence</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>39,298</p></td><td><p>1,549,892</p></td><td><p>955,242</p></td><td><p>2,544,432</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>32,290</p></td><td><p>1,580,051</p></td><td><p>994,775</p></td><td><p>2,607,116</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>27,790</p></td><td><p>1,397,993</p></td><td><p>891,110</p></td><td><p>2,316,893</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>23,719</p></td><td><p>1,138,522</p></td><td><p>741,506</p></td><td><p>1,903,747</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>21,980</p></td><td><p>841,077</p></td><td><p>588,500</p></td><td><p>1,451,557</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>21,831</p></td><td><p>667,877</p></td><td><p>517,228</p></td><td><p>1,206,936</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>22,341</p></td><td><p>567,087</p></td><td><p>418,527</p></td><td><p>1,007,955</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>23,338</p></td><td><p>494,614</p></td><td><p>395,808</p></td><td><p>913,760</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Prescription Cost Analysis (PCA) NHS Digital</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>Prescriptions are written on a prescription form known as an FP10. Each single item written on the form is counted as a prescription item.</p><p> </p><p>PCA Data</p><p><br> Prescription information is taken from the PCA system, supplied by NHS Prescription Services, a division of NHS Business Services Authority, and is based on a full analysis of all prescriptions dispensed in the community i.e. by community pharmacists and appliance contractors, dispensing doctors, and prescriptions submitted by prescribing doctors for items personally administered in England. Also included are prescriptions written in Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland and the Isle of Man but dispensed in England. The data do not cover drugs dispensed in hospitals, including mental health trusts, or private prescriptions.</p><p> </p><p>Prescribers are general practitioners, hospital doctors, dentists and non-medical prescribers such as nurses and pharmacists.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>British National Formulary (BNF) Classifications</p><p> </p><p>The PCA system uses the therapeutic classifications defined in the BNF using the classification system prior to edition 70. Information on why a drug is prescribed is not available in this dataset. Since drugs can be prescribed to treat more than one condition, it may not be possible to separate the different conditions for which a drug may have been prescribed.</p><p> </p><p>The primary purpose of the BNF is to provide information for clinicians. The format of the BNF was changed with Edition 70 (September 2015 - March 2016) to make it more user friendly. However, the NHS Business Service Authority, who process dispensed prescription forms and collects dispensed prescribing data and produce the PCA data, continue to use the old BNF classification system to code medicines, which has become widely used in the United Kingdom as a classification to allow comparisons between drug groups. For example, it is used to report cost and trend in medicines use and supports several NHS Digital official publications. The data are used in many NHS IT systems.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077717/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T16:34:30.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077717/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077717/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-26","Nicotine Replacement Therapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the number of prescriptions dispensed in the community for nicotine replacement therapy in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","226130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077719","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-06","<p>There is no central National Health Service collection of information on nicotine replacement therapy dispensed in hospitals in England.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077719/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T16:33:11.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077719/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077719/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-26","Nicotine Replacement Therapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how his Department records prescriptions for nicotine replacement therapy dispensed in hospital; how many such prescriptions were dispensed in each year since 2010; whether he plans to increase the number of those prescriptions dispensed in hospital; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","226131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077720","Department for Education","true","2019-03-04","<p>The department currently employs 209 apprentices. This can be broken down into the following groups in the attached table, which also shows the proportion against the total number of employees.</p><p>Regarding the proportion of apprentices employed at the Institute for Apprenticeships, this is a matter for the Institute for Apprenticeships and Technical Education. I have asked the Chief Executive, Sir Gerry Berragan, to write to the hon. Member for Ashton-under-Lyne and a copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p><p>Within the Education and Skills Funding Agency, 5 employees working on apprenticeships strategy, policy and delivery are apprentices, which represents 1.6% of the total of 317 employees.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077720/answer","226124_226125_226126_table_of_apprentices_employed_by_the_Department_for_Education.doc","226124_226125_226126_table_of_apprentices_employed_by_the_Department_for_Education.doc","226124_125_126_Table_of_apprentices","226124_125_126_Table_of_apprentices",,"2019-03-04T15:34:53.567Z","2019-03-07T17:32:32.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077720/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077720/answer","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077720/answer/previousversion/104932","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077720/answer/previousversion/104932","226124_226125_226126_table_of_apprentices_employed_by_the_Department_for_Education.doc","226124_226125_226126_table_of_apprentices","60","Education","Education","2019-02-26","Department for Education: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of staff employed in each group of his Department that are apprentices.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","226124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077721","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-05","<p>The Government has been very clear that leaving the EU will not lead to a lowering of our high animal welfare standards, and is making good on our commitment to make the UK a world leader in the care and protection of animals as we leave the EU.</p><p>Our regulatory system will offer at least the same level of assurance of animal welfare following our departure from the EU as it does now. The EU Withdrawal Act will ensure that existing EU standards are maintained once we leave the EU. For instance, existing bans on imports of chlorinated chicken and hormone beef have been transferred into UK law and will remain in place after we leave.</p><p>We are actively exploring options for strengthening the UK system moving forward. These include plans to increase maximum penalties for animal cruelty from six months’ to five years’ imprisonment. We are also considering what more can be done to improve animal welfare standards in the context of our future agricultural policy and are looking to control exports of live animals for slaughter.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077721/answer",,,,,"226199","2019-03-05T10:22:05.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077721/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077721/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-02-26","Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans his Department has to maintain animal rights through legislation after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Damien Moore","Southport","Damien Moore","226212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077722","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-06","<p>The Government has stated its aim to establish a far-reaching science and innovation pact with the European Union, facilitating the exchange of ideas and researchers, and enabling the United Kingdom to participate in key programmes alongside our EU partners.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to securing a Withdrawal Agreement with the EU. However, as a responsible Government, we continue to prepare for all scenarios, including ‘no deal’. As part of these preparations, the Government is working across a range of workstreams to understand the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU without a deal, and to ensure that the UK has the best possible environment for basic, biomedical, health, and life sciences research. This includes access to and mobility of research leaders and the technical and research delivery workforce; access to EU research funding; the regulation of clinical trials, data and devices; rare diseases research; and clinical trials supplies in a ‘no deal’ scenario.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077722/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-06T16:28:50.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077722/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1077722/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-26","Medicine: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on health research of the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Damien Moore","Southport","Damien Moore","226213"
